Ethanol (4 mL) was added into the okara sample (ECO, AOO, MRO, LAO or OKR) and the suspension was stirred at 1500 rpm overnight at room temperature. The mixture was then centrifuged (5000 rpm, 20 °C, 5 min) and the supernatant was stored at 4 °C until usage. 75 mM p-nitrophenyl α-d-glucopyranoside (100 μL) as the substrate was pre-mixed with the ethanolic okara extract (10 μL) at different concentrations (50, 100, 250, 500, 1000 μg/mL) in a 96-well plate. α-glucosidase (250 U/L, 100 μL) was then added to each well to initiate the enzymatic reaction. The reaction was then allowed to run at 37 °C for 20 min. α-Glucosidase activity was determined by measuring the release of p-nitrophenol from the p-nitrophenyl α-d-glucopyranoside complex expressed by an increase of absorbance at 405 nm. α-Glucosidase activity of the sample was then calculated relative to the control (no extract) following Eq. 1 below.1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
